<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="507" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,258,1398]" box="[199,1320,1158,1183]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1159,1183]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Etymology:</emphasis>
Dedicated to Gloria Ariza, mantid specialist at the Universidad del Tolima (
<collectingCountry box="[1191,1308,1158,1182]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Colombia</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,258,1398]" box="[199,375,1194,1219]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,375,1194,1219]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">
<taxonomicName box="[199,289,1194,1219]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Markia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hystrix">Hystrix</taxonomicName>
Group
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,258,1398]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">
The species of this group are medium-sized (
<quantity box="[709,836,1230,1254]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" unit="mm" value="52.0" valueMax="54.0" valueMin="50.0">50–54 mm</quantity>
). Pronotal spines are enlarged; at least the metazonal spine is distinctly longer than the fastigium. Spines of the legs are elongated, outer margin of hind femur with seven or eight spines projecting towards the sides, the sixth spine being usually strongly raised beyond the dorsal margin. Branches of the cerci are armed with ventral or apical denticulations. The known distribution of this group is mostly Central American, with one species in the Colombian Pacific coast and possibly extending to 
<collectingCountry box="[1310,1406,1374,1398]" name="Ecuador" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
